etymologies: late 19th century; earliest use found in George Allman (1812–1898), naturalist. From Hellenistic Greek ϕυλακτός capable of being preserved (from ancient Greek ϕυλακ-, stem of ϕυλάσσειν to guard + -τός, suffix forming verbal adjectives), though used in active sense, ‘capable of guarding or protecting’ + καρπός fruit

definitions: A receptacle in certain hydrozoans protecting the gonothecae.
